<br>
There's nothing wrong with you for wanting some of that back.  But take a look at yourself.  I'd also wager that you have stopped doing many things that made him initially so attracted to you in the first place.<br>
<br>
Maybe I am out of line by saying that, but it is what I observe in most other relationships.  <br>
<br>
I hope you will take the fact that this new guy is sexy completely out of the equation though.<br>
<br>
Ok, so.  My advice.  I second that you need to stop seeing this man outside of work.  To say that any human is immune to temptation is folly.  People can be subject to temptation, and be partially innocent for their ensuing actions.  HOWEVER.  You have COMPLETE control over whether or not the situations conductive to that temptation ever occur.  Bad things are happening with this guy, get away from him.  If you both love your respective spouse, and continue to see eachother, you'll end up hurting 4 people.<br>
<br>
-Takkon <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wiestrum>Wiestrum</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 89<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/10/03 12:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1906.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Ok, So I need advice...(long)</span><hr size=1> He also could be trying to seduce you to put another notch in his bedpost...in spite of his wife. My &quot;friend&quot; would sleep with anyone if given half a chance and I still don't know why his wife hasn't divorced him yet. Are you sure this isn't the same kind of thing here? <br>
<br>
Flirting is fun. It helps build confidence in both people...but it's also dangerous. Most married people no longer flirt with each other, because they don't need to. People spend most of their single adult life looking for a partner and flirting is a way to let someone else know you are interested. If it's gone on this long and you feel this way, your marriage is probably already over. The only thing left is the small details and they will rip your heart apart. <br>
<br>
Get marriage counseling, now. If your husband doesn't want to go, go alone. Anyone who has ever gone through a divorce can tell you how hard it can be. It rips your own self-identity apart because after awhile your identity is entwined with that of your partner. If you think you can handle the emotional pain and being alone, then by all means, continue with what you are doing. Just realize that if he's flirting with you, he's probably flirting with someone else and the way he's treating his wife, will be the same way he'll treat you.<br>
<br>
I guess my advice is that you're makeing a big mistake!<br>
<br>
